<DOC sysid="rbmt-1" docid="idnes.cz/2012/12/01/494025" genre="news" origlang="cs">
<h1>
<seg id="1">Poland space.</seg>
</h1>
<p>
<seg id="2">Last week at the ministerial session of European Space Agency Poland was accepted by the twentieth member of European Space Agency as the second country from the countries of the former eastern block (after the Czech Republic, which it became full-fledged term EKA on September 12, 2008).</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="3">Poland began close collaboration with EKA in 1994 and for the subsequent years was accepted active participation in a number of the projects of agency.</seg>
<seg id="4">But way to space Poland began much earlier.</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="5">Even before the Second World War Polish enthusiasts dealt with voyages into space, but this was not always encountered with the understanding.</seg>
<seg id="6">I will resemble, for example, about A. Sternfeld's lecture, who on December 6, 1933 represented in the Warsaw astronomical observatory of idea from his innovative work “introduction into cosmonautics”.</seg>
<seg id="7">The ideas of young engineer (1905 g. r.) left the audience of indifferent, Sternfeld recalled after several years, that only the doctor Ian Gadomskiy was interested in his work.</seg>
<seg id="8">In 1934 in France Sternfeld won reward of Robert to Esnaupeltrie and Andre Louis Khirsha for “the introduction into cosmonautics”.</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="9">The doctor Ian Gadomskiy (1899 - 1966), whom was discussed above, more lately became the great propagandist of astronomy and cosmonautics.</seg>
<seg id="10">It published in Polish periodicals hundreds of articles and wrote the row of the books, dedicated to these scientific disciplines.</seg>
<seg id="11">Gadomskiy became the well-known world propagandist of cosmonautics, and his contribution was evaluated including by the fact that one of the craters on the far side of the moon was named in its honor.</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="12">In Poland was already in 1925 built the railroad trolley, equipped with rocket engine.</seg>
<seg id="13">Unfortunately, the author of this idea remained unknown, just as to the detail of project.</seg>
<seg id="14">It is not clear even, for the acceleration or for braking of cart had to be used the rocket.</seg>
<seg id="15">Information about this trolley is known only from the press of that epoch.</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="16">Since 1933 Polish artillery began to think about the rocket arrows.</seg>
<seg id="17">A study accomplished the section of the technology of weapon with the collaboration with professors Mechislav Volfke and Gustav Mokzhitsky.</seg>
<seg id="18">It is evident from the preserved materials that studies reached the stage of service tests.</seg>
<seg id="19">But works were interrupted with the arrival of German troops.</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="20">In 1937 in the specialized press the idea of the photoelectric of rocket-fighter, which proposed engineer Rogozinskiy, appeared, and in the following year published work “air rocket-torpedo and aviation rocket-bomb” author Lelivy-Kzhivoblotskogo.</seg>
<seg id="21">Both projects were developed for the military use of rocket engines.</seg>
<seg id="22">Before war itself with all designs of the military use of rocket engineering dealt the temporary scientific-consultative committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy), which coordinated entire work.</seg>
<seg id="23">Committee was created in 1937, but after two years of its activity work ended because of the beginning of war.</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="24">The following scientific work, dedicated to cosmonautics, appeared in the Polish press after war, because of the work of the Polish society of astronautics (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).</seg>
<seg id="25">About the society are for the first time mentioned during by Noyabrsk number of 1954 of the journal “problems”, in which are published four volumetric articles on the astronautics.</seg>
<seg id="26">In one of them the professor of M. sub-OTOHIV proposed to organize the society, which will be occupied by cosmonautics.</seg>
<seg id="27">At that time the designs of satellites already collected revolutions, and it was clear that space studies - promising branch.</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="28">Since the beginning of 1956 the Polish society of astronautics (POA) attempted to enter the international federation of astronautics (based in 1951), and already in autumn POA became its full member.</seg>
<seg id="29">But in the following year the first chairman of POA Kazimezh Zarankevich (1902 - 1959) became the deputy chairman of the international federation of astronautics.</seg>
<seg id="30">On this post it remained to its quite death, which began in 1959.</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="31">Since 1956 POA made the significant contribution to development of very successful sounding rocket RM (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), which became the first Polish rocket, which carried out scientific research.</seg>
<seg id="32">The first type RM-1 was completed in 1957, while the first starting took place on October 10, 1958.</seg>
<seg id="33">The rocket, capable of covering the distance of 1800 m, there were into the length of approximately 80 cm, and its weight comprised less than 5 kg.</seg>
<seg id="34">Was subsequently built the improved version RM-1A, and in the summer of 1959 on the Bledovskom vacant land were carried out testing two-stage rocket RM-2.</seg>
<seg id="35">This rocket was into the length of approximately 1,4 m, and its weight was about 11.5 kg.</seg>
<seg id="36">The following version of rocket was able be occupied to already by this scientific work - rocket RM-34 could overcome 14.5 km, and observation of the wind at high altitudes was its task.</seg>
<seg id="37">But in 1962 further development was stopped.</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="38">The successor of the first rockets of the type RM became rocket Meteor-1, developed in the period between 1962 and 1965.</seg>
<seg id="39">Rocket was planned as its two-step, overall length it was 510 cm, and initial weight - 32.5 kg.</seg>
<seg id="40">Were developed three types (designated as Meteor-1A, -1V and -1S), which were distinguished by the size of camera for the scientific equipment.</seg>
<seg id="41">Rocket Meteor-1A had available space with a volume of 0.4 l, Meteor-1V - 0.34 l, and Meteor-1S - 0, 62l.</seg>
<seg id="42">Maximum flying distance in all three types was 37 km.</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="43">In the period between 1965 and 1968 the development of rocket in the aviation institute passed Meteor-2, and its first flight tests began in October 1970.</seg>
<seg id="44">Rocket Meteor-2 with a launching weight of 380 kg was capable of deriving payload with the weight of 10 kg on the height of approximately 60 km.</seg>
<seg id="45">Then were built versions Meteor-2N and Meteor-3.</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="46">It is worthwhile to also mention about the entry of Poland in COSPAR (Committee on Space Research) in 1960 and creation of the national committee of COSPAR by two for years later.</seg>
<seg id="47">Furthermore, within the framework of the program Interkosmos, Poland participated in the space research on the Soviet satellites, and in 1978 Polish pilot Miroslav Germashevskiy became the second interkosmonavtom after Vladimir Remek.</seg>
</p>
</doc>
